# protected-paths
#
# Patterns whose matching files protect-paths shadows with /dev/null inside
# the container at startup, so they appear as empty files regardless of
# their contents on the host.
#
# Format (one pattern per line, all paths relative to workspace root):
#
#   path/to/file              exact relative path
#   **/<basename>             every file matching <basename> anywhere in the
#                             workspace. <basename> is a fnmatch pattern with
#                             '/' disallowed (e.g. **/.env, **/.env.*.local).
#                             Build/dependency dirs (node_modules, .git,
#                             .tsc-build, dist, build, .next, .yarn) are
#                             pruned from the search.
#   <dir>/**                  every regular file under <dir>, recursively.
#   !<pattern>                exclusion. Same three shapes as above. A file
#                             that matches any include AND any exclusion is
#                             left unmasked. Order-independent (gitignore-
#                             style negation). Use for checked-in fixtures
#                             that live next to real secrets.
#
# Blank lines and lines starting with '#' are ignored. Absolute paths and
# paths containing '..' are rejected. Patterns that don't match anything on
# the host are skipped silently.

# .env files. The chosen basenames mirror the deny rules in
# .devcontainer/config/initialize.sh and the .gitignore convention:
#   .env             — the file dotenv.config() loads
#   .env.local       — Next.js auto-loads this in every mode except test
#   .env.*.local     — Next.js per-mode override (.env.production.local etc.)
# Checked-in fixtures (.env.example, .env.template, .env.test_shadow,
# example.env) and the per-mode defaults file (.env.production, which is
# checked into git by Next.js convention) are intentionally not masked.
**/.env
**/.env.local
**/.env.*.local
